When it comes to replacing the contents of a page with the contents of a different URL without adding a new page to the navigation stack, you have two primary options: using AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) or `location.replace()`. While both methods achieve the desired result, they work in different ways and have distinct use cases.

### Using AJAX

AJAX is a technique for dynamically updating a web page without requiring a full page reload. When you use AJAX to fetch data from a different URL, the browser doesn't navigate to the new URL, and the page's history is not updated.

Here's an example of how you might use AJAX to replace the contents of a page with the contents of a different URL:
```javascript
// Send an AJAX request to fetch data from the new URL
fetch('/new-url')
  .then(response => response.text())
  .then(data => {
    // Update the page's content with the received data
    document.getElementById('page-content').innerHTML = data;
  });
```
